<h2>Translating message content into other languages</h2>
<p>Some patients may not understand written English. You should make all possible efforts to meet their communication needs.</p>
<ol>
  <li>Ask patients to tell you their preferred written language.</li>
  <li>Record this preference in their health record.</li>
  <li>Include this information when referring patients to other healthcare professionals.</li>
  <li>Translate message content into a patient's preferred language whenever possible.</li>
</ol>
<p>You should:</p>
<ul>
  <li>provide the original message to the translator in plain English</li>
  <li>consider if recording a spoken interpretation may be a better option if the person has a low level of literacy</li>
  <li>consider if visual content like images and diagrams may be more helpful</li>
  <li>consider if a phone call with a translator might be more appropriate if the message is important</li>
</ul>
<p>Avoid Google Translate and other automated online translation services. The translations could be poor quality.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/language-interpretation-migrant-health-guide">Find out more about language interpreting and translation for healthcare practitioners on GOV.UK.</a></p>
